# The Future of React Server Components

React Server Components (RSC) represent one of the most significant architectural shifts in the React ecosystem since the introduction of Hooks.

## Why RSC?

Traditionally, single-page applications shipped megabytes of JavaScript to the client just to render static content. RSC flips this paradigm by keeping the rendering heavy lifting strictly on the server.

### Key Benefits
- **Zero Bundle Size Impact**: Components rendered on the server add absolutely zero kilobytes to your client JS bundle.
- **Direct Backend Access**: You can natively access databases and microservices seamlessly within your component structure.
- **Enhanced SEO**: By delivering structured HTML right from the start, web crawlers instantly parse the complete DOM.

```javascript
// Example of a Server Component
import db from 'lib/database';

export default async function TopStories() {
  const stories = await db.query('SELECT * FROM stories LIMIT 10');

  return (
    <ul>
      {stories.map(story => (
        <li key={story.id}>{story.title}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

As frameworks like Next.js continue refining the App Router experience, embracing the Server Component architecture is becoming mandatory for creating high-performance experiences without sacrifices.

# Architecting Design Systems with Tailwind v4

With the release of Tailwind v4, the reliance on external configuration scripts has vanished, replaced by an elegant highly-optimized CSS directive architecture.

## The Power of Native CSS Variables

Instead of relying heavily on `tailwind.config.js`, v4 allows complete integration natively inside ***raw CSS***:

```css
@theme {
  --color-brand-500: #7c3aed;
  --font-display: 'Space Grotesk', sans-serif;
}
```

By unifying standard CSS Custom Properties with Tailwind's generated utilities, building dynamic dark modes and scalable component libraries is faster and vastly more readable.
